04514nam a22006975i 9780824837235DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20122012hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248372357 a10.1515/97808248372352doi  a(DE-B1597)484045  a(OCoLC)1076409410  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBQ9399.T337bH37 2013eb 7aREL0920002bisacsh04a294.34204272231 aHaskel, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSword of Zen :bMaster Takuan and His Writings on Immovable Wisdom and the Sword Taie /cPeter Haskel. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. An Introduction to Takuan’s Writings on Zen and Swordsmanship -- t2. Translations -- t3. Happenings in a Dream -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTakuan Sōho’s (1573–1645) two works on Zen and swordsmanship are among the most straightforward and lively presentations of Zen ever written and have enjoyed great popularity in both premodern and modern Japan. Although dealing ostensibly with the art of the sword, Record of Immovable Wisdom and On the Sword Taie are basic guides to Zen—“user’s manuals” for Zen mind that show one how to manifest it not only in sword play but from moment to moment in everyday life.Along with translations of Record of Immovable Wisdom and On the Sword Taie (the former, composed in all likelihood for the shogun Tokugawa Iemitsu and his fencing master, Yagyū Munenori), this book includes an introduction to Takuan’s distinctive approach to Zen, drawing on excerpts from the master’s other writings. It also offers an accessible overview of the actual role of the sword in Takuan’s day, a period that witnessed both a bloody age of civil warfare and Japan’s final unification under the Tokugawa shoguns. Takuan was arguably the most famous Zen priest of his time, and as a pivotal figure, bridging the Zen of the late medieval and early modern periods, his story (presented in the book’s biographical section) offers a rare picture of Japanese Zen in transition.For modern readers, whether practitioners of Zen or the martial arts, Takuan’s emphasis on freedom of mind as the crux of his teaching resonates as powerfully as it did with the samurai and swordsmen of Tokugawa Japan. Scholars will welcome this new, annotated translation of Takuan’s sword-related works as well as the host of detail it provides, illuminating an obscure period in Zen’s history in Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSwordplayzJapanxPhilosophy. 0aZen BuddhismxDoctrines. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Zen (see also PHILOSOPHY / Zen).2bisacsh1 aHaskel, Peter.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483723540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824837235423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824837235.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK